##  Hardware Connections

| ESP32-S3 Pin | Connected To | Function |
|---|---|---|
| `GPIO41` | HC-SR04P `TRIG` | Ultrasonic trigger pulse output |
| `GPIO42` | HC-SR04P `ECHO` | Ultrasonic echo pulse input |
| `GPIO14` | SG90 Servo signal | PWM servo control (50 Hz, 500–2400 µs pulse range) |
| `GPIO45` | Active Buzzer `+` | Digital obstacle alert output  *strapping pin, see warning below* |
| Camera data/clock/SCCB pins | OV2640 module | Defined in `camera_pins.h` *(not provided — board-specific)* |
| 5V / 3.3V + GND | All peripherals | Shared ground required for stable HC‑SR04P + servo + buzzer operation |

>  **Important Notes & Warnings**
> - `GPIO45` is an ESP32-S3 **strapping pin** used during boot to select VDD_SPI voltage. Pulling it high/low externally at boot (e.g. via the buzzer wiring) can affect boot behavior — this is flagged directly in the firmware's pin definitions and should be tested carefully on real hardware.
> - `pulseIn()` on the `ECHO` pin can block the CPU for up to `SONAR_TIMEOUT_US` (30 ms). The firmware mitigates this by limiting ultrasonic reads to once per `SONAR_INTERVAL_MS` (100 ms) rather than making it fully non-blocking.
> - The servo is allocated to **LEDC timer 1** specifically to avoid clashing with **LEDC timer 0**, which the camera driver uses for the XCLK signal — do not change this without checking for timer conflicts.

